births <- openintro::births14

Describing & Observing

# find the describe function to be very useful, preferred visually
describe(births)

# since it doesnt make NAs clear though:
sum(is.na((births))) # know I have 231 missing values
[1] 231
births[!complete.cases(births), ] # returns 206 rows, so at least 2 missing values
missingValues <- as.data.frame(colSums(is.na(births)))
missingValues %>%
  filter(`colSums(is.na(births))` > 0)

Encoding of Variables

  • categorical: mature, premie, lowbirthweight, sex, habit, marital, whitemom

  • interval: weeks

  • ratio: fage, mage, visits, gained, weight

Missing Values Observations:

  • Fathers age accounts for ~49% of our missing data

  • Visits to the hospital account for ~24%

  • Weight Gained by the mother is ~18%

  • Smoking Habit covers ~8%

tail(births, 5)

# graphing with ggplot
graphMature <- ggplot(births, aes(mature)) + geom_bar(stat = "count") + geom_text(stat = "count", aes(label = ..count..), vjust = 1, size = 2.75)
graphPremie <- ggplot(births, aes(premie)) + geom_bar(stat = "count") + geom_text(stat = "count", aes(label = ..count..), vjust = 1, size = 2.75)
graphLowBW <- ggplot(births, aes(lowbirthweight)) + geom_bar(stat = "count") + geom_text(stat = "count", aes(label = ..count..), vjust = 0.8, size = 2.75)
graphSex <- ggplot(births, aes(sex)) + geom_bar(stat = "count")  + geom_text(stat = "count", aes(label = ..count..), vjust = 1, size = 2.75)
graphHabit <- ggplot(births, aes(habit)) + geom_bar(stat = "count") + geom_text(stat = "count", aes(label = ..count..), vjust = 1, size = 2.75)
graphMarital <- ggplot(births, aes(marital)) + geom_bar(stat = "count")  + geom_text(stat = "count", aes(label = ..count..), vjust = 1, size = 2.75)
graphWhite <- ggplot(births, aes(whitemom)) + geom_bar(stat = "count") + geom_text(stat = "count", aes(label = ..count..), vjust = 1, size = 2.75)

graphMature + graphPremie + graphLowBW + graphSex + graphHabit + graphMarital + graphWhite + plot_layout(ncol = 3) & theme_pander()

Notes: Not too much interesting in these graphs

Potential Later Inquiries: perhaps might find something in further segmentation like by low birth weight by child sex, mother maturity, mother race, marital status

Two different ways of expressing similar concepts but I personally feel the boxplots to be a bit more informative in that it makes our outliers clearer in context of the lower/upper ranges of normal for the population.

Some observations:

  • Appear to be pretty normally distributed with some small skews

    • Pregnancy in Weeks is skewed to the left

    • Weight Gained by Mother during Pregnancy is skewed to the right.

  • Fathers tend to be older than mothers

  • If theyre an outlier, more likely that the pregnancy will be shorter than longer.

  • Mothers are more likely to gain more weight than normal while babies are more likely to have lower weights at birth than normal

Testing

Random Sampling

# would strongly prefer to not have to edit my analysis every rerun, thanks
set.seed(12)
# only 10% to ensure that things remain cool, independence wise
sampleBirths <- births[sample(nrow(births), 100, replace = FALSE), ]
describe(sampleBirths)

Correlations

pairs(~ fage + mage + weeks + visits, 
      data = sampleBirths, 
      na.action = na.omit)

pairs(~ fage + mage + gained + weight, 
      data = sampleBirths, 
      na.action = na.omit)

pairs(~ mage + weeks + gained + weight, 
      data = sampleBirths, 
      na.action = na.omit)

No part of me is surprised by the seemingly tight correlation between mothers age and fathers age, that is how that usually goes.

round(cor(sampleBirths[ , c("fage", "mage", "weeks", "visits", "gained", "weight")], use = "complete.obs"), 2)
        fage  mage weeks visits gained weight
fage    1.00  0.78  0.12  -0.03  -0.11   0.07
mage    0.78  1.00  0.17   0.06  -0.07   0.12
weeks   0.12  0.17  1.00   0.23  -0.09   0.63
visits -0.03  0.06  0.23   1.00  -0.06   0.11
gained -0.11 -0.07 -0.09  -0.06   1.00  -0.13
weight  0.07  0.12  0.63   0.11  -0.13   1.00

Correlation matrix confirms what we would have thought about the mothers and fathers age at a moderate-to-strong 0.78. And based on the graphs, I didnt fully expect much to come from this in that manner, everything does look pretty scattered. The babys weight and weeks of pregnancy are the strongest correlation on the board (other than the obvious of correlation with the same variable), which makes sense as theyve had a bit more time to bake in the oven.

round(cor(sampleBirths[1:50, c("fage", "mage", "weeks", "visits", "gained", "weight")], use = "complete.obs" ), 2)
        fage  mage weeks visits gained weight
fage    1.00  0.76  0.09   0.02  -0.10   0.07
mage    0.76  1.00  0.19   0.02  -0.13   0.19
weeks   0.09  0.19  1.00   0.02   0.09   0.53
visits  0.02  0.02  0.02   1.00  -0.35  -0.07
gained -0.10 -0.13  0.09  -0.35   1.00  -0.03
weight  0.07  0.19  0.53  -0.07  -0.03   1.00

The second had nothing to do with anything really, it was just interesting to see how little it takes to change the numbers.

  • While not by much, mother and fathers ages are less correlated.

  • Mothers weight gained is now more strongly correlated with the babys weight gain.

Linear Regression

May not turn up much but perhaps, looking into the strongest correlation?

effect on weight given weeks

model <- lm(sampleBirths$weight ~ sampleBirths$weeks)

model
